": "TheDonald", "ad_tier": 2, "last_comment_author": "Ficklepimper", "is_video": false, "video_link": "", "is_new_user": false, "domain": "media.scored.co", "is_crosspost": false, "preview": "https://media.scored.co/preview/1ASZf4j9df.png", "removal_source": "", "link": "https://media.scored.co/post/yWtYSGZbXACo.jpeg", "author_flair_class": "", "is_removed": false, "media": {"resized_resolutions": [{"reference": "/scale/LxD5dvIXcvfdwNOd.png", "width": 533, "content-type": "png", "height": 768}], "blurhash": "UTQmCqRjj]M{9FayWBRk?bazofof~qazt6t7", "full_resolution": [1441, 1000]}, "title": "Diversity\u2122 is Canada's military strength:  After Canada started accepting non-citizens into the military, report shows ethnic infighting and a complete breakdown in ability to communicate ", "last_comment_created": 1777564049390, "content": "", "score_down": 0, "author_flair_text": "", "pro_tier": 0, "is_stickied": false, "is_nsfw": false, "is_deleted": false, "is_image": true, "comments": 3, "score_up": 25, "is_edited": false, "is_moderator": false, "awards": 0, "vote_state": 2, "link_metadata": {"status": 200}, "post_flair_text": "", "archive_id": ""}, {"is_locked": false, "tweet_id": "", "sticky_comment": 0, "is_video_mp4": false, "type": "text", "uuid": "1ASZf4j9VJ", "is_twitter": false, "is_admin": false, "score": 26, "suggested_sort": 0, "post_flair_class": "", "id": 8591361, "raw_content": "Thermal receipts aren\u2019t just paper. The coating that lets the print appear with heat is where the issue is.\n\nMost receipts used to contain BPA. Many now use BPS instead, which was supposed to be safer but behaves similarly in the body. Both are linked to hormone disruption. The amount you absorb from a single receipt is small, but the transfer happens through skin, and it adds up if you\u2019re handling them all day.\n\nAbsorption is higher if your hands are wet, greasy, or covered in sanitizer or lotion. That combination makes it easier for the chemicals to pass through the skin. That\u2019s why cashiers and people in retail are the main group of concern, not someone who takes a receipt once in a while.\n\nThere\u2019s also indirect exposure. The residue can move from the receipt onto your hands, then onto food, your phone, or anything else you touch. Keeping receipts in your pocket or wallet means that contact continues longer than necessary.\n\nThey\u2019re also not recyclable in normal paper streams because of that coating, so they end up contributing to environmental contamination.\n\nPractical handling is straightforward. Don\u2019t take a receipt unless you need it. Wash your hands before eating if you\u2019ve handled one. Don\u2019t rely on hand sanitizer alone. If you\u2019re handling receipts constantly, reduce skin contact where possible and avoid using lotions right beforehand.\n\nFor most people, this is a low-level risk. It becomes a real consideration with repeated, daily exposure over time.\n\n\n(Maybe this is why so many in certain industries are Gay?)", "author": "HeNotMedicated", "created": 1777562082545, "profile_picture": "", "community": "TheDonald", "ad_tier": 2, "last_comment_author": "freeperjim", "is_video": false, "video_link": "", "is_new_user": false, "domain": "", "is_crosspost": false, "preview": "", "removal_source": "", "link": "", "author_flair_class": "", "is_removed": false, "media": {"resized_resolutions": [], "blurhash": "", "full_resolution": []}, "title": "REMINDER: Thermal Receipts are dangerous to your health and should not be touched. They have forever chemicals that disrupt human hormones / sexuality. Like the receipts on your Starbucks Cup. Ya. Those.", "last_comment_created": 1777565762351, "content": "<p>Thermal receipts aren\u2019t just paper. The coating that lets the print appear with heat is where the issue is.</p>\n<p>Most receipts used to contain BPA. Many now use BPS instead, which was supposed to be safer but behaves similarly in the body. Both are linked to hormone disruption. The amount you absorb from a single receipt is small, but the transfer happens through skin, and it adds up if you\u2019re handling them all day.</p>\n<p>Absorption is higher if your hands are wet, greasy, or covered in sanitizer or lotion. That combination makes it easier for the chemicals to pass through the skin. That\u2019s why cashiers and people in retail are the main group of concern, not someone who takes a receipt once in a while.</p>\n<p>There\u2019s also indirect exposure. The residue can move from the receipt onto your hands, then onto food, your phone, or anything else you touch. Keeping receipts in your pocket or wallet means that contact continues longer than necessary.</p>\n<p>They\u2019re also not recyclable in normal paper streams because of that coating, so they end up contributing to environmental contamination.</p>\n<p>Practical handling is straightforward. Don\u2019t take a receipt unless you need it. Wash your hands before eating if you\u2019ve handled one. Don\u2019t rely on hand sanitizer alone. If you\u2019re handling receipts constantly, reduce skin contact where possible and avoid using lotions right beforehand.</p>\n<p>For most people, this is a low-level risk. It becomes a real consideration with repeated, daily exposure over time.</p>\n<p>(Maybe this is why so many in certain industries are Gay?)</p>\n", "score_down": 0, "author_flair_text": "", "pro_tier": 0, "is_stickied": false, "is_nsfw": false, "is_deleted": false, "is_image": false, "comments": 3, "score_up": 26, "is_edited": false, "is_moderator": false, "awards": 0, "vote_state": 2, "link_metadata": {"status": 200}, "post_flair_text": "", "archive_id": ""}], "status": true}